We first extract the required numbers from the financial statements. In our case:

• Operating Cash Flow from the cash flow statement (Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities): –7,724,112.71  
• Current Liabilities (from the balance sheet, “Total Current Liabilities”): 737,762.05  
• Inventory – Beginning is 0 and Ending Inventory is 5,550,000.00 (so average inventory = (0 + 5,550,000.00)/2 = 2,775,000.00)  
• Cost of Goods Sold from the income statement: 4,680,000.00  
• Total Liabilities: (we only have “Total Current Liabilities”): 737,762.05  
• Total Owner’s Equity from the balance sheet: 11,647,620.37  
• Current Assets from the balance sheet (“Total Current Assets”): 6,951,011.84  
• To calculate Quick Assets: subtract Inventory from Current Assets = 6,951,011.84 – 5,550,000.00 = 1,401,011.84

Now we compute:

1. Operating Cash Flow Ratio = Operating Cash Flow / Current Liabilities  
  = –7,724,112.71 / 737,762.05 ≈ –10.47

2. Cash Flow to Debt Ratio = Operating Cash Flow / (Total Debt)  
  Since our only debt is current liabilities, this ratio is also  
  = –7,724,112.71 / 737,762.05 ≈ –10.47

3. Inventory Turnover Ratio = Cost of Goods Sold / Average Inventory  
  = 4,680,000.00 / 2,775,000.00 ≈ 1.69

4. Debt to Equity Ratio = Total Liabilities / Total Owner’s Equity  
  = 737,762.05 / 11,647,620.37 ≈ 0.06

5. Quick Ratio = Quick Assets / Current Liabilities  
  = 1,401,011.84 / 737,762.05 ≈ 1.90

6. Current Ratio = Total Current Assets / Current Liabilities  
  = 6,951,011.84 / 737,762.05 ≈ 9.42

Thus, the solution is:

  }
